## Problem Statement
Electrocardiogram (ECG) signals are essential for monitoring heart activity and detecting cardiac abnormalities, but they are very weak and easily affected by noise such as power-line interference, muscle movements, baseline wander, and motion artifacts. These unwanted signals reduce the accuracy of ECG analysis and make it difficult to obtain a clear waveform. In addition, many commercial ECG monitoring systems are expensive and not easily accessible for educational, research, and low-cost healthcare applications. Therefore, there is a need for a portable, affordable, and reliable ECG acquisition system that can accurately capture heart signals while minimizing noise.

## Proposed Solution
To address this problem, this project develops a low-cost ECG Acquisition and Noise Filtering system using an Arduino Uno, AD8232 ECG sensor, OLED display, and SD card module. The AD8232 sensor acquires real-time ECG signals from electrodes placed on the body, while the Arduino processes the acquired data and applies basic noise filtering techniques to improve signal quality. The filtered ECG waveform is displayed in real time on the OLED display, and the acquired data is stored on the SD card for future analysis. This portable system provides an economical and efficient solution for ECG monitoring, making it suitable for educational purposes, embedded systems research, and basic healthcare applications.
